<br>
I was brought up by parents of rather mixed religious backgrounds. My mother is Anglican, whereas my dad was brought up under astrict dutch reformed(almost calvanist) religious background. I guess both have influenced me in some ways.<br>
<br>
<br>
From my own experiences - many occuring in a different coutries....so the lifestyle are different.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What I like about the Christian religion:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> First off, a place of worship, is an excellent place to come and meet people. I've always lived in rural areas, and the church becomes a place for people who usually lead quite individual lifestyles to unite. It brings communities together and encourages (especially in the dutch reformed teachings) very strong moral beliefs. Sunday school, as sad as it may sound, HAS taught me an awfull lot of what is right and wrong in life. Learning about the parodies and discussing them is a VERY good groundwork for future free thinking. It also teaches yet more moral values - respect your elders etc.etc. When you see 10 year old kids wandering around the streets swearing and causing trouble... you sometimes wonder..you know.<br>
They dont teach morality in school. They teach not to bully, or not to steal - not to do this, not to do that.... but they dont place the foundations for good living.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What I don't like about the Christian religion:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
First off - the class system. Sometimes the church was split by elitetism. The rich kept away from the poor, or the proffesionals keep away from the farmers. The radical liberals stay away from the conservatives. Wrong.<br>
Secondly,the way many vicors,rectors etc. teach the bible is rubbish. They teach the writings literally. Does anyone here take George Orwells' <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Animal Farm</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> literally? This is in my opinion the Church greatest downfall. The stark belief by many of upper hierarchy that people need to be taught everything literally, and directly as written. From here stem the preachings, that so many non-Christians probably venomously oppose.<br>
And then we have the age old problem of power...<br>
<br>
It's a shame that something so good at providing the backbone to human existance, has become so flawed. Its no surprise that the European Christian Church is collapsing so quickly - people aren't stupid.<br>
<br>
A final note - I don't think believing in Science makes religion obsolete  - it enhances it.<br>
<br>
Good topic btw.<br>
<br>
Dash <p><CENTER><HR>
